  "verdict": "Q (PR #556): is lawine #544's int4-HEAD +38 byte-exact under strict #319, or is the strict-safe head ceiling below 292? MEASURED (deployed int4_g32): flip_rate_heldout=0.00029 (29/101222), _ood=0.00021 (2/9378). int4_head_is_319_strict=False: int4 head FLIPS the greedy argmax on EVERY corpus (rate>0 incl. held-out) -> NOT #319-byte-exact via a plain precision swap. Corrected strict_safe_head_ceiling_tps=252.31 (precision='bf16'): NO plain head precision (int4 any granularity, fp8, int8) is byte-exact AND faster than bf16, so the strict-safe ship has NO plain-precision head lever and is HARD-CAPPED at the bf16 floor 252.31; the program's headline '~292' is reachable ONLY via fern #549's candidate-verify, never a plain precision swap. CORPUS-DEPENDENCE (the load-bearing cross-check): int4_g128 flip rate held=0.00049 / ood=0.00043 / OFFICIAL-128=0.01384 vs fern's math-mix 0.0212 -- NL/code is ~43x below fern while my official-128 reproduces fern-class rates, so the apparatus is confirmed and the gap is a real near-tie-density effect (flip rate tracks workload). Stage-3 locus (held-out g32, 29 flips): int4_flip_is_near_tie_concentrated=True -- flips sit in a thin margin band (flip median 0.122 vs non-flip median 8.58, ~71x separation); a near-tie verify at margin<0.5 catches >=90% of flips touching only 0.0018 of positions -> a SMALL fern #549 candidate-verify K_safe provably covers the flips.",
